  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\nEarly Precursors:\n1. Traditional banking regulations first emerged in the early 20th century to combat financial fraud\n2. Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts were primarily focused on combating organized crime\n\nKey Milestones:\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (1970, United States)\n- First comprehensive legislation targeting financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established framework for tracking potential illicit financial activities\n\nInternational Developments:\n1. Basel Committee Guidelines (1980s)\n2. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment in 1989\n3. United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n\nSignificant Expansion Post-9/11:\n1. USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Dramatically expanded AML regulatory requirements\n- Increased reporting and monitoring obligations\n- Enhanced international information sharing mechanisms\n\nModern Trends:\n1. Increased digital currency and cryptocurrency regulations\n2. Expanded international cooperation\n3. More sophisticated detection technologies\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve, addressing emerging financial technologies and global economic challenges.",
